# Changelog

To install the unreleased agentgrep version:

[pip](https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/):

```console
$ pip install --user --upgrade --pre agentgrep
```

[pipx](https://pypa.github.io/pipx/docs/):

```console
$ pipx install \
    --suffix=@next \
    --pip-args '\--pre' \
    --force \
    'agentgrep'
```

Run the suffixed executable as:

```console
$ agentgrep@next [command]
```

[uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/):

```console
$ uv add agentgrep --prerelease allow
```

[uvx](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/guides/tools/):

```console
$ uvx --from 'agentgrep' --prerelease allow python
```

## agentgrep 0.1.0a5 (Yet to be released)

<!-- KEEP THIS PLACEHOLDER - DO NOT REMOVE OR MODIFY THIS LINE -->

agentgrep 0.1.0a5 grows the CLI from three subcommands to five, with
each new surface mirroring a tool users already know: `agentgrep
grep` matches `rg` / `ag` for content search, `agentgrep find` grows
fd-shaped flag grammar for store enumeration, and a new `agentgrep
fuzzy` provides `fzf --filter`-style non-interactive fuzzy filtering
over stdin. A new `--ui` overlay flag turns any subcommand into its
TUI form — the `tig` model for git, applied to agentgrep. Bare
`agentgrep` now prints a colorized directory of choices listing
every subcommand, matching the `tmuxp` / `vcspull` convention; the
TUI is reachable through the explicit `agentgrep ui` subcommand.
Output for `grep` is now line-aware (one row per matching line with
the matched span highlighted) and `find` defaults to one path per
line — both following rg's and fd's lead. A new `--no-progress`
flag silences the stderr spinner in one keystroke. Under the
covers, a new headless event-stream engine yields typed pydantic
events as the search walks; the CLI consumes the stream live so
the first matches appear within milliseconds instead of after the
full scan finishes. Output alignment lands deeper in this release:
`grep`'s default pipe shape is now rg-faithful `path:text` (with
`-n` / `--column` / `--vimgrep` opt-ins), `grep -c` emits
`path:N` per matching record, `grep --json` is now rg's per-line
event stream with `submatches[*]` carrying byte offsets, and
`find` with no positional pattern lists every source (fd parity).
A new Lucene-style query language threads field predicates,
boolean composition, and date ranges through `search`, `grep`,
and `find` while keeping the legacy fast path zero-cost when
the syntax isn't used: write `agentgrep search agent:codex bliss`
or `agentgrep search '(agent:codex OR agent:cursor) AND deploy
timestamp:>2026-01-01'` to mix source-level pruning with record-
level filtering. A combinatorial stress test against the rg/fd
contract surfaced six more alignment gaps, all addressed in this
release: `grep` now surfaces a clean error for invalid regex (no
more Python tracebacks), refuses empty patterns at parse time,
drops the trailing blank line under `-o`, and refuses `-v` for
text output until engine-level line invert lands ([#8](https://github.com/tony/agentgrep/issues/8)); `grep -L` now
lists sources with no matches (previously a stub); and `find -g`
matches against the file basename by default with a new
`--full-path` flag for absolute-path matching (fd's `-p`).

### Breaking changes

#### `grep` default text shape is now `path:text` (rg-faithful)

`agentgrep grep` previously emitted `path:line:col:text` for every
match — essentially always-vimgrep, regardless of flags. The new
default mirrors `rg`'s pipe shape: `path:text`. Opt back into
prefixes with `-n` / `--line-number` for `path:line:text`, with
the new `--column` flag for `path:line:col:text`, or with
`--vimgrep` for the legacy one-row-per-match-span shape.

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep grep bliss
~/.codex/.../a.jsonl:1:5:The bliss primitive ships with serene defaults

# After (rg-faithful)
$ agentgrep grep bliss
~/.codex/.../a.jsonl:The bliss primitive ships with serene defaults

# After + --column (legacy shape)
$ agentgrep grep --column bliss
~/.codex/.../a.jsonl:1:5:The bliss primitive ships with serene defaults
```

#### `grep -c` emits `path:N` per matching record

`agentgrep grep -c` previously emitted a single integer counting
matching records. The new shape mirrors `rg -c`: `path:N` per
matching record (counting matching *lines*), or just `N` when
exactly one record matched.

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep grep -c bliss
2

# After
$ agentgrep grep -c bliss
~/.codex/.../a.jsonl:3
~/.codex/.../b.jsonl:1
```

#### `grep --json` is now an rg-shaped per-line event stream

`agentgrep grep --json` previously emitted one `match` event per
record with `line_number: null` and the full multi-line record
text in `data.text`. The new shape mirrors `rg`'s `--json`
contract: per matching line, an event with nested `path.text`,
1-indexed `line_number`, `lines.text` (the matched line), and
`submatches[*].{match: {text}, start, end}` carrying byte offsets.
Each record is bookended with `begin` and `end` events; the
envelope still closes with a `summary` event. Consumers built
against `rg --json` can route agentgrep's stream through the same
parser.

```json
// Before
{"type":"match","data":{"path":"...","line_number":null,
  "text":"...defaults\nno match...\nanother bliss..."}}

// After
{"type":"begin","data":{"path":{"text":"..."},...}}
{"type":"match","data":{"path":{"text":"..."},"line_number":1,
  "lines":{"text":"The bliss primitive..."},
  "submatches":[{"match":{"text":"bliss"},"start":4,"end":9}]}}
{"type":"end","data":{"path":{"text":"..."},
  "stats":{"matched_lines":1,"matches":1}}}
{"type":"summary","data":{"matches":1}}
```

#### Bare `agentgrep` no longer launches the TUI

Bare `agentgrep` (with no subcommand) now prints a colorized
directory of choices — the same pattern `tmuxp` and `vcspull` use —
listing each subcommand with example invocations. The interactive
Textual explorer is reachable only through the explicit `ui`
subcommand:

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep

# After
$ agentgrep ui
```

The behavior change aligns agentgrep with the tmuxp/vcspull
conventions users coming from those tools already expect.

#### `agentgrep <terms>` no longer auto-runs `search`

The implicit shorthand that rewrote `agentgrep <terms>` as
`agentgrep search <terms>` is removed. Bare positionals now produce
argparse's standard `invalid choice` error so the available
subcommands stay discoverable. Migration is to spell the subcommand
out:

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep bliss

# After
$ agentgrep search bliss
```

#### `agentgrep find` default pattern is now regex

`agentgrep find <PATTERN>` now treats `PATTERN` as a regex by default
to match fd's behavior. The previous behavior (literal substring) is
available via `-F` / `--fixed-strings`. Plain alphanumeric patterns
match identically under both modes; users whose patterns contain
regex metacharacters should pass `-F`:

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep find 'foo.bar'

# After
$ agentgrep find -F 'foo.bar'
```

#### `agentgrep find -g` matches against the path basename

`agentgrep find -g GLOB` previously applied the glob to a joined
`agent store adapter_id path path_kind` haystack, so `*.jsonl`
returned "No matching sources found" even though every store path
ended in `.jsonl`. The new default matches the glob against the
file basename (fd's default behavior); a new `--full-path` flag
opts into matching the absolute path (fd's `-p`). Regex, fixed,
and exact modes are unchanged — they still match the joined
haystack so `agentgrep find sessions` continues to hit on the
store fragment.

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep find -g '*.jsonl'
No matching sources found.

# After (basename matching)
$ agentgrep find -g '*.jsonl'
~/.codex/sessions/2026/05/a.jsonl
~/.codex/sessions/2026/05/b.jsonl

# After + --full-path (absolute path matching)
$ agentgrep find -g '*/sessions/*.jsonl' --full-path
~/.codex/sessions/2026/05/a.jsonl
```

#### `agentgrep grep` text output is now line-aware

`agentgrep grep` previously dumped each matching record's full text
field verbatim, which on a multi-line prompt or transcript could
fill the terminal. The new default emits one line per matching line
within a record — `line:col:text` rows with the matched span
highlighted (red+bold). On TTY each record opens with a heading
line (agent · timestamp · path); on pipe every match emits as
`path:line:col:text` so the output stays grep-pipeline friendly.
The format mirrors `rg` and `ag`. JSON, NDJSON, `--vimgrep`, `-c`,
`-l`, and `-L` are unchanged; `--vimgrep` and `-o` now produce real
line/col offsets (previously hardcoded `1:1`).

#### `agentgrep find` default is one path per line

`agentgrep find` previously printed three lines per record (agent
header, path, blank). The new default emits one path per line,
matching `fd`. The metadata (agent, kind, store, adapter_id) is
still reachable through the existing `-l/--list-details` flag,
which produces a tab-separated long format. `--json`, `--ndjson`,
and `--print0` are unchanged.

### Dependencies

Adds runtime dependency `rapidfuzz>=3.10.0`. The new `agentgrep
fuzzy` subcommand *is* the fuzzy library — unlike the pydantic /
textual / fastmcp pattern of optional deps with fallbacks, fuzzy has
no useful fallback, so rapidfuzz is a hard dep.

### What's new

#### Headless event-stream engine

agentgrep grows a typed event-stream engine that powers the CLI,
TUI, and MCP server from one producer. Two new public iterators —
{func}`agentgrep.iter_search_events` and
{func}`agentgrep.iter_find_events` — yield pydantic-discriminated
{data}`~agentgrep.events.SearchEvent` and
{data}`~agentgrep.events.FindEvent` values as the engine walks
sources, so consumers can react per-record instead of waiting for
the full list.

`agentgrep grep` and `agentgrep find` consume the stream live: text
and NDJSON output rows appear within milliseconds of the first
match, with stdout flushed per record when stdout is a TTY. The
eager output modes (`--json`, `-c`, `-l`, `-L`, `--list-details`)
keep using the existing list-return wrapper because their output
shape needs the final tally or cross-record deduplication. See
{ref}`library-event-stream` for the architecture walkthrough,
event vocabulary, and consumer recipes.

#### `--no-progress` flag and `find --progress`

`grep`, `search`, and `find` now accept `--no-progress` as an alias
for `--progress=never`, silencing the stderr spinner with one
flag. `find` also gains the full `--progress {auto,always,never}`
selector it previously lacked. Progress always writes to stderr, so
piping (`agentgrep grep foo | less`) was never affected — the new
flag is for interactive sessions where the spinner is noise.

#### `agentgrep grep` content search

A new `agentgrep grep` subcommand mirrors `ripgrep` and
`the_silver_searcher`. The flag set carries the rg conventions
users already type: `-F` / `-E` / `-w` for pattern mode, `-i` / `-s`
/ `-S` for case (smart-case default), `-c` / `-l` / `-L` / `-o` /
`-v` for output filtering, `-m` for match caps, `--vimgrep` and
`--json` for output shapes, and `--no-dedupe` to drop session
deduplication for the strictly rg-faithful raw view. Exit codes
follow grep's 0/1/2 convention. See {ref}`cli-grep` for the
walkthrough.

#### `agentgrep fuzzy` non-interactive fuzzy filter

A new `agentgrep fuzzy` subcommand provides fzf's `--filter` mode:
read lines from stdin, score them with the v2 fuzzy algorithm
(`--algo=v1` for the older quality-blend), and emit matches in
descending score order. Supports fzf's extended-search syntax (`foo
!bar`, `^foo`, `bar$`, `'foo`), `--read0` / `--print0` for
NUL-delimited pipelines, `--delimiter` / `--nth` / `--with-nth` for
field-scoped scoring, and `--print-query` for echoing the query.
The no-argument behavior is strict — no QUERY and no piped stdin
prints usage and exits `2` (no interactive TUI fallback; reach for
`agentgrep ui` instead). See {ref}`cli-fuzzy`.

#### fd-shaped flags on `agentgrep find`

`agentgrep find` grows the fd flag set: `-g` / `--glob` for
fnmatch-style patterns, `-F` for literal substring, `--exact` for
adapter-id equality, `-t` / `--type` to filter by record kind
(`prompts` / `history` / `sessions` / `all`), `-e` / `--extension`
to filter by file extension (repeatable), `-i` / `-s` for case
override (smart-case default), `-l` / `--list-details` for a long
tab-separated format, `-0` / `--print0` for NUL-delimited output
to feed `xargs -0`, and `-a` / `--absolute-path` (symbolic, paths
are already absolute). See {ref}`cli-find` for the new examples.

#### `--ui` overlay across all subcommands

A new `--ui` flag on `grep`, `find`, and `fuzzy` (the existing
`search --ui` is unchanged) opens the Textual explorer pre-filled
with the same query the one-shot command would have run. This is
the `tig`-shaped overlay model — `agentgrep grep -i foo --ui` is to
`agentgrep grep -i foo` what `tig log` is to `git log`. Same args,
same query semantics, different presentation.

#### `find --full-path` for fd `-p` parity

`agentgrep find -g GLOB` matches the path basename by default;
`--full-path` switches the glob to the absolute path, matching
fd's `-p` semantic. Useful when the basename alone isn't enough to
disambiguate (e.g. you want every `*.jsonl` under `sessions/` but
not under `history/`). See {ref}`cli-find` for examples.

#### Lucene-style query language across search/grep/find

`agentgrep search`, `agentgrep grep`, and `agentgrep find` now
accept inline Lucene-style field predicates, boolean composition,
and date ranges as part of the positional arguments. Plain
positionals (no `:`) keep the legacy fast path with zero overhead.

```console
$ agentgrep search agent:codex bliss
$ agentgrep search '(agent:codex OR agent:cursor) AND deploy'
$ agentgrep search '-agent:claude timestamp:>2026-01-01 bliss'
$ agentgrep find 'path:~/.codex agent:codex'
```

The default field registry ships ten fields split across two
evaluation layers. Source-level fields (`agent`, `store`,
`adapter_id`, `path`, `mtime`) prune sources before any file is
opened — `agent:codex` skips Claude / Cursor / Gemini sources
entirely. Record-level fields (`type`, `timestamp`, `model`,
`role`, `text`) filter parsed records after the source pass.
Date literals accept ISO (`2026-05-22`, `2026-05`, `2026`,
`2026-05-22T14:30:00`), relative (`today`, `yesterday`,
`7d ago`, `2w ago`, `5d from now`), and unbounded (`*`) forms.
Bare-day equality expands to a 24-hour half-open range; bare-month
to the calendar month; bare-year to the calendar year.

Boolean composition supports explicit `AND` / `OR` / `NOT` (case-
insensitive whole-word keywords), the sigils `-` (NOT) and `+`
(no-op, accepted for rg compatibility), and parens for grouping.
The compiler uses three-valued logic during the source-prune
pass so OR-mixed queries (source-layer OR'd with record-layer)
degrade safely — the source is read and the record predicate
decides.

Mixing the new field syntax with the equivalent flag is rejected
at parse time:

```console
$ agentgrep search --agent codex agent:claude bliss
agentgrep search: error: cannot combine --agent flag with agent: field predicate; pick one syntax
```

Currently checked: `--agent` × `agent:`, `--type` × `type:`.
Unknown field names error at parse time with the registered
field list. Invalid regex / unparseable date / unknown enum
value each produce a clean argparse-shaped error with exit 2,
never a Python traceback.

See {ref}`library-query-language` for the full grammar, field
registry, and date literal reference.

#### `--ui` overlay accepts the full query language

Launching the TUI via `agentgrep search --ui agent:codex bliss`
now opens with the full query string in the search box (not just
the text terms), and editing the box re-parses field syntax on
every keystroke — `agent:codex bliss` becomes
`agent:claude deploy` becomes `timestamp:>2026-01 OR model:claude`
without restarting the TUI. Field predicates that prune sources
take effect on the next debounced re-search. Parse / compile
errors keep the search box editable so users can correct typos
in-flight.

### Fixes

#### Query language: invalid enum + date literals now error at parse time

`agentgrep search agent:gpt4 bliss` used to scan 1,400+ sources for
~20 seconds and silently return "No matches found." because enum
validation lived in the source-side evaluation path, which the
eager search path didn't trigger. The compiler now walks the AST
once at parse time and rejects unknown enum values
(`agent:gpt4`, `type:bogus`), unparseable date literals
(`timestamp:>bogus`, `mtime:[bogus TO 2026]`), and the wrong-op-
for-field combinations (`agent:>codex`, `type:[a TO b]`). Users
see a clean argparse-shaped exit-2 error with the valid choices
listed.

#### Query language: `search`'s eager path now prunes sources

`agentgrep search agent:codex bliss` was paradoxically *slower*
than the unfiltered `agentgrep search bliss` because the eager
path's `collect_search_records` never consulted the compiled
query's source predicate — every source got opened just to be
rejected at the record level. The source predicate now runs in
`search_sources` *before* the ripgrep prefilter, so non-codex
sources skip both planning and reading. The agent-filtered search
is now faster than the unfiltered baseline, as it always should
have been.

#### Query language: `-agent:claude` no longer silently mangles into short flags

`agentgrep find -agent:claude` (unquoted negation shortcut) used
to silently parse as the combined short options `-a -g -e
nt:claude` because each leading character matched a defined short
flag — turning the user's negation intent into a glob-mode search
with extension filter `nt:claude`. A pre-scan now rejects argv
tokens shaped like `-FIELD:VALUE` (where FIELD is a known query
field) at parse time, with a clean error suggesting the
workarounds: `--` separator, quoted positional, or `NOT` keyword.

#### `agentgrep find` with no pattern lists every source

`fd` with no positional pattern lists every file. `agentgrep find`
with no positional was printing `--help` and exiting because
`parse_args` had an early-return for the missing pattern. The
engine already accepts `pattern=None` as "no filter"; removing the
early return restores fd-parity:

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep find
usage: agentgrep find [...]

# After (fd-faithful)
$ agentgrep find
~/.codex/.../a.jsonl
~/.codex/.../b.jsonl
~/.claude/.../session.jsonl
```

#### `agentgrep grep` invalid regex emits a clean error

`agentgrep grep '['` previously dumped a Python traceback ending in
`re/_parser.py` and exited 1 — the unprotected `re.search` call
inside the engine had no boundary guard. `grep` now validates
every pattern at the argparse layer (with the same case + word
wrapping the engine uses) and surfaces an argparse-shaped error
on failure:

```console
# Before
$ agentgrep grep '['
Traceback (most recent call last):
  ...
re.PatternError: unterminated character set at position 0

# After
$ agentgrep grep '['
usage: agentgrep grep [...]
agentgrep grep: error: invalid regex '[': unterminated character set at position 0
```

Exit code is now 2 (matching rg / grep convention for usage
errors). `-F` (fixed strings) skips validation since literal
patterns never reach `re.compile`.

#### `agentgrep grep` rejects empty patterns

`agentgrep grep ''` previously short-circuited through
`iter_match_lines`'s zero-width-match filter and emitted a
find-shaped `agent  [ts]  path` line — visually indistinguishable
from `agentgrep find` output. The empty pattern is now refused at
parse time with the standard argparse shape (git-grep parity):

```console
$ agentgrep grep ''
usage: agentgrep grep [...]
agentgrep grep: error: pattern cannot be empty
```

The check applies to every term, so `agentgrep grep foo ''` still
fails.

#### `agentgrep grep -o` no longer emits trailing blank lines

`agentgrep grep -o PATTERN` was leaking the heading-mode blank-line
separator after every record, so the output looked like
`bliss\n\nbliss\n\n...` instead of rg's bare `bliss\nbliss\n...`.
The separator is now suppressed under `-o`, restoring rg parity.

#### `agentgrep grep -v` for text output is refused at parse time

`agentgrep grep -v PATTERN` previously accepted the flag and then
silently returned the records that *did* contain PATTERN —
inversion was only honored under `-c` and `-L`. Until engine
support for line-level invert lands
([#8](https://github.com/tony/agentgrep/issues/8)), `-v` outside
`-c`/`-L` is rejected at parse time with exit 2 so users get a
clean error instead of wrong-but-plausible output.

```console
$ agentgrep grep -v bliss
agentgrep grep: error: --invert-match for text output is not yet
implemented (see https://github.com/tony/agentgrep/issues/8); use
-c or -L
```

`-v -c` and `-v -L` still parse — both collapse to the
"did anything match?" question the engine's existing surface can
answer.

#### `agentgrep grep -L` lists sources with no matches

`agentgrep grep -L PATTERN` was a stub returning empty stdout
regardless of input. The new implementation runs the same query
the engine would run, collects matching paths from the event
stream, and prints the complement against the engine's planned
source set. Exit codes follow rg: `0` when at least one path is
printed, `1` when every planned source matched.

```console
$ agentgrep grep -L bliss
~/.codex/sessions/2026/05/b.jsonl
```

### Development

#### `agentgrep.cli` subpackage

The CLI surface — argument parsing, output rendering, subcommand
dispatch — moves out of `src/agentgrep/__init__.py` into a new
`src/agentgrep/cli/` subpackage with `parser.py`, `render.py`, and
an entry-point shim. The console script `agentgrep` now resolves
through `agentgrep.cli:main`. All previously public symbols
(`parse_args`, `SearchArgs`, `run_search_command`, etc.) are
re-exported from `agentgrep` for backward compatibility, so any
external code or test importing them via the package namespace
continues to work unchanged.

#### `agentgrep.fuzzy` helper module

A new `src/agentgrep/fuzzy.py` wraps `rapidfuzz` so the rest of the
codebase never imports it directly. Exposes
`resolve_case_sensitivity`, `fuzzy_score` (algo v1/v2),
`extended_match` for fzf's token grammar, and `rank_lines` as a
sorted iterator. Tests live in `tests/test_fuzzy.py`.

